# DwarfSpec component-testing refactor

## Goal

Replace the fixture-oriented live UI API with a Cypress-style component-testing
model. A test mounts one DFHack UI component into a DwarfSpec-owned live
harness, and all later commands implicitly operate on that mount or on a fluent
subject selected from it.

The refactor is complete when ordinary widgets, overlay widgets, and complete
screens all use the same `ds.mount()` entry point; consumers do not implement
render counters; and tests do not pass fixture screens or raw views between
normal `ds` commands.

## Decisions

- Busted remains responsible for discovery, suites, examples, hooks,
  assertions, and result classification.
- DwarfSpec commands retain synchronous-looking coroutine semantics. This work
  does not introduce Cypress's deferred JavaScript command queue.
- `ds.mount(component, options)` is the only component mount operation.
- A mount accepts an ordinary `widgets.Widget`, an `overlay.OverlayWidget`, or
  a complete `gui.ZScreen`, either as a supported constructor/class or as an
  already-created instance.
- DwarfSpec owns the mount harness, render instrumentation, current-mount
  context, synchronization, diagnostics, and cleanup.
- A Busted example has at most one active mount. Mounting another component
  cleanly unmounts the current component before installing its replacement.
- `ds.get(view_id)` searches the current mount and returns a DwarfSpec subject,
  not a raw DFHack view.
- Subject commands are fluent, for example `ds.get('submit'):click()`.
- Busted and Luassert remain the assertion API. DwarfSpec subjects expose
  stable values and diagnostics for assertions but do not add a parallel
  `should()` assertion language.
- Render generations are private DwarfSpec state. Consumers never add or
  maintain a `render_generation` field.
- Overlay widgets use `ds.mount()` like every other component. Any helper for
  proving overlay script discovery, configuration, or registration is an
  integration facility, not a separate overlay mount operation.
- Test-support factories remain ordinary Lua helpers. There is no required
  DwarfSpec fixture-module protocol or mandatory fixture directory.

## Target authoring experience

```lua
local TooltipOverlay =
    reqscript('gui/dwarfui-tooltip').OVERLAY_WIDGETS.tooltip

describe('tooltip overlay', function()
    before_each(function()
        ds.mount(TooltipOverlay, {
            message='Example tooltip',
        })
    end)

    it('shows its tooltip while hovering', function()
        ds.get('trigger'):hover()

        local tooltip = ds.await('tooltip becomes visible', function()
            local subject = ds.get('tooltip')
            return subject:inspect().visible and subject
        end)

        assert.equals('Example tooltip', tooltip:text())
    end)
end)
```

Escape hatches such as `subject:raw()` may expose a native object for uncommon
product-specific assertions, but ordinary selection and interaction must not
require raw views.

## Public API target

- mount context: `ds.mount`, `ds.root`, `ds.unmount`;
- selection: `ds.get`;
- synchronization: `ds.await`, `ds.wait_frames`;
- subject interaction: `click`, `hover`, `move_pointer`, `input`, `type`;
- subject observation: `inspect`, `text`, and an explicit raw-view escape
  hatch;
- evidence: mount-scoped view-tree and screen capture commands.

The final method names and return values must be documented and covered by
contract tests before the legacy fixture API is removed.

## Phase 1: Characterize the component boundary

- [ ] Add unit characterization for constructing and identifying a plain
  `widgets.Widget`, an `overlay.OverlayWidget`, and a `gui.ZScreen`.
- [ ] Define unambiguous rules for constructor/class inputs versus component
  instances and reject unsupported values with actionable errors.
- [ ] Define the mount options common to every component, including viewport
  size, component attributes, initial pause behavior, and optional backing
  viewscreen context.
- [ ] Define whether constructor failures, initialization failures, and first
  render failures are reported as mount failures or host errors.
- [ ] Record the minimum DFHack APIs required by the live mount adapters.
- [ ] Add a public API contract test that reserves `mount`, `root`, `unmount`,
  and the initial subject methods.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] The three supported component categories and both supported input forms
  have executable contract tests.
- [ ] No adapter behavior depends on product-specific classes or paths.

## Phase 2: Build the run-owned mount context

- [ ] Add a mount-context module owned by one automation run.
- [ ] Track the current mount, root component, host screen, private render
  generation, selected subjects, and cleanup entries without storing test
  metadata on consumer components.
- [ ] Implement `ds.mount(component, options)` and `ds.unmount()` against the
  mount context.
- [ ] Implement `ds.root()` as a subject for the current component root.
- [ ] Make all mount-context references weak where ownership does not require a
  strong reference.
- [ ] Make a second `ds.mount()` fully unmount and settle the previous mount
  before constructing the replacement.
- [ ] Produce clear errors for `root`, `get`, interaction, or unmount commands
  when no component is mounted.
- [ ] Register mount cleanup before showing or activating a component so a
  partial mount failure remains reversible.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Unit tests cover initial mount, replacement mount, explicit unmount,
  partial mount failure, and operations without a current mount.
- [ ] Cleanup leaves no active screen or pending mount entry after every case.

## Phase 3: Own render instrumentation

- [ ] Add a private render tracker that can wait for a generation greater than
  a captured generation without requiring a component field.
- [ ] Instrument the DwarfSpec host screen's completed render path for mounted
  widgets and overlay widgets.
- [ ] Instrument a mounted complete screen's effective `onRender` path without
  requiring the screen class to cooperate.
- [ ] Preserve the original complete-screen render behavior and restore any
  instance interception during cleanup.
- [ ] Increment generations only after successful completed renders.
- [ ] Route mount, click, hover, input, type, resize, and other mutating
  operations through the private render tracker.
- [ ] Capture bounded screen and component-tree diagnostics when mounting or
  rendering fails.
- [ ] Remove the `render_generation` requirement from the public fixture and
  interaction contracts.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Live tests prove automatic generation changes for a plain widget, an
  overlay widget, and a complete screen whose source contains no DwarfSpec
  instrumentation.
- [ ] A render failure retains the original error plus mount diagnostics.

## Phase 4: Implement the ordinary-widget adapter

- [ ] Create a generic DwarfSpec `ZScreen` host for ordinary widgets.
- [ ] Mount the component as the host's root content without mutating its class.
- [ ] Propagate layout, visibility, activation, focus, input, and resize through
  normal DFHack widget behavior.
- [ ] Ensure the mounted component receives a real painter and real live frame
  bodies.
- [ ] Associate descendants with the owning mount automatically after layout
  and after dynamic subtree changes.
- [ ] Restore the prior pause state and dismiss the host during unmount.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] A live component test can mount a product-independent widget, locate a
  descendant, click it, type into it, inspect it, and unmount it without ever
  receiving or passing the host screen.

## Phase 5: Implement the overlay-widget adapter

- [ ] Accept `overlay.OverlayWidget` through the same `ds.mount()` dispatcher.
- [ ] Reuse the generic host screen and private render tracker instead of
  installing a GUI script.
- [ ] Assign an isolated run-owned logical name when the caller did not provide
  one.
- [ ] Apply test-local frame positioning without reading or writing persisted
  overlay configuration.
- [ ] Use the correct scaled, full-interface, or fullscreen painter contract.
- [ ] Emulate applicable `overlay_onenable`, `overlay_onupdate`, `onInput`, and
  `overlay_ondisable` lifecycle calls in the same order as the DFHack overlay
  framework.
- [ ] Supply an explicit backing viewscreen context to callbacks that normally
  receive one.
- [ ] Cover visible, active, fullscreen, full-interface, update-throttled, and
  input-handling behavior.
- [ ] Document that isolated mounting intentionally bypasses script discovery,
  persisted enablement and position, viewscreen/focus filtering, hotspot
  registration, and overlay database registration.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] The same mount, selection, interaction, synchronization, and cleanup
  tests pass for ordinary and overlay widgets.
- [ ] No public method named `mount_overlay`, `show_overlay_fixture`, or similar
  exists.

## Phase 6: Implement the complete-screen adapter

- [ ] Accept `gui.ZScreen` through the same `ds.mount()` dispatcher.
- [ ] Show the supplied screen directly rather than placing it inside another
  covering screen.
- [ ] Install and remove automatic render interception on the mounted instance.
- [ ] Preserve native screen activation, dismissal, parent input forwarding,
  and pause-state behavior.
- [ ] Associate the complete screen and all descendants with the current mount.
- [ ] Verify modal and child-screen behavior without allowing an unowned screen
  to become the implicit component root.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Complete-screen component tests use the same `ds.mount`, `ds.get`, and
  fluent subject commands as widget tests.
- [ ] The tested screen has no test-only render counter or lifecycle hook.

## Phase 7: Add implicit selection and fluent subjects

- [ ] Implement `ds.get(view_id)` against only the current mount's propagated
  view-id index.
- [ ] Return a run-owned subject wrapper containing the selected view and mount
  identity.
- [ ] Reject stale subjects after unmount or replacement mount.
- [ ] Move view-oriented operations from `ds` functions onto subjects:
  `click`, `hover`, `move_pointer`, `input`, `type`, `inspect`, and `text`.
- [ ] Make interaction methods return a useful subject so compatible commands
  can be chained.
- [ ] Define when a command preserves the subject, changes it, or returns a
  scalar observation.
- [ ] Keep command execution immediate within the live coroutine; do not add a
  deferred command queue.
- [ ] Add `subject:raw()` as an explicitly documented escape hatch and ensure
  internal APIs never require callers to use it.
- [ ] Make mount-scoped capture commands infer the current root.
- [ ] Include the selected view id and current mount identity in failures and
  retained diagnostics.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Representative tests use `ds.get('id'):click()` and Busted assertions
  without passing a fixture, screen, root, or raw view to normal commands.
- [ ] Unit tests cover fluent return behavior, stale subjects, duplicate ids,
  missing ids, and dynamic view-tree changes.

## Phase 8: Harden lifecycle and failure recovery

- [ ] Run mount reset before and after every Busted example.
- [ ] Preserve strict LIFO cleanup for component, host screen, pointer state,
  pause state, lifecycle callbacks, and render interception.
- [ ] Ensure assertion failures, command errors, render errors, timeouts,
  external lease expiry, and explicit abort all drain mount resources.
- [ ] Make cleanup idempotent after explicit unmount or replacement mount.
- [ ] Report cleanup failures without hiding the originating test failure.
- [ ] Retain bounded mount-tree and screen captures for failed interactions.
- [ ] Confirm that a failed example cannot leak its current mount or subjects
  into the following example.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Resilience unit tests cover every terminal path.
- [ ] Live abort and timeout reports have `cleanup_confirmed=true` and leave no
  DwarfSpec-owned screen active.

## Phase 9: Separate component and overlay-integration coverage

- [ ] Migrate overlay behavior tests to `ds.mount(OverlayWidget, options)`.
- [ ] Retain a minimal integration test for real `OVERLAY_WIDGETS` discovery,
  registration, rescan, enablement, positioning, focus filtering, and cleanup.
- [ ] Keep any run-owned script staging helper internal unless consumers have a
  demonstrated need to author registration integration tests.
- [ ] Ensure an integration helper cannot overwrite product scripts or persist
  configuration changes.
- [ ] Name and document integration tests distinctly from component tests.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Overlay component behavior is proven without copying files into
  `hack/scripts/gui`.
- [ ] The smaller integration suite proves the DFHack overlay boundary and
  restores every modified external artifact.

## Phase 10: Remove the fixture protocol and migrate consumers

- [ ] Replace DwarfSpec's `show_fixture` self-tests with direct component
  mounts.
- [ ] Replace `stage_overlay_fixture` behavior tests with overlay component
  mounts, retaining only the integration coverage identified above.
- [ ] Migrate DwarfUI live specs to direct mounts and fluent subjects.
- [ ] Convert reusable fixture modules into ordinary constructors, data
  builders, or product-independent test-support helpers.
- [ ] Remove manual `render_generation` fields and `on_automation_shown` hooks
  from consumer test components.
- [ ] Remove or formally deprecate `ds.show_fixture`, `ds.dismiss(screen)`, and
  `ds.stage_overlay_fixture` after all in-repository consumers migrate.
- [ ] Remove fixture-loader and overlay-fixture modules that have no remaining
  integration responsibility.
- [ ] Confirm the configurable `*.ds.lua` discovery contract continues to
  exclude conventional `*.fixture.lua` and support files by default.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] Repository search finds no consumer-authored `render_generation`, no
  normal interaction that passes a root or screen, and no obsolete fixture API
  usage.
- [ ] DwarfSpec and DwarfUI unit and live suites pass against the same installed
  rock artifact.

## Phase 11: Documentation and release proof

- [ ] Rewrite the writing guide around `ds.mount()` and fluent subjects.
- [ ] Document constructor, instance, ordinary-widget, overlay-widget, and
  complete-screen examples.
- [ ] Document component-test isolation versus real overlay-plugin integration.
- [ ] Update the architecture document to replace fixture ownership with mount
  context and adapter ownership.
- [ ] Update the command reference and changelog for removed or deprecated
  methods.
- [ ] Run Lua 5.3 and Lua 5.4 syntax checks and the complete DwarfSpec unit
  suite.
- [ ] Run rockspec lint, pack the rock, inspect its manifest, and install it into
  an empty LuaRocks tree.
- [ ] Run DwarfSpec's product-independent live component matrix from the
  installed rock.
- [ ] Run the migrated DwarfUI live suite from that exact installed artifact.
- [ ] Verify deterministic JSON reports and `cleanup_confirmed=true` for pass,
  failure, timeout, and abort runs.

Exit evidence:

- [ ] All public documentation presents one component-testing model centered
  on `ds.mount()`.
- [ ] Installed-package tests prove ordinary widgets, overlay widgets, and
  complete screens through identical author-facing commands.

## Completion checklist

- [ ] One `ds.mount()` operation supports all three component categories.
- [ ] No consumer implements DwarfSpec render counters.
- [ ] Normal commands infer the current mount and use fluent subjects.
- [ ] Busted remains the only test and assertion framework.
- [ ] Component tests do not install overlay scripts.
- [ ] Overlay registration integration remains testable and reversible.
- [ ] Every live terminal path confirms cleanup.
- [ ] DwarfSpec and DwarfUI pass locally and against the same installed rock.
